article.description: Katie Smith scored 27 points, and rookie Nicole Ohlde had a career-high five blocks to lead the Minnesota Lynx to a 68-52 victory Thursday night over the poor-shooting Connecticut Sun.
article.headline: Sun shoot just 32 percent in loss
article.linkText: Smith's 27 points, Ohlde's 5 blocks lead Lynx
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Minnesota's inside-outside combination
of Katie Smith and Nicole Hold was more than the Connecticut Sun
could handle.

Smith scored 27 points, tying her career-best of six 3-pointers.
Hold, the 6-foot-5 rookie center, had a career-high five blocks in
the Lynx's 68-52 victory Thursday night.

It was the sixth straight win for the Lynx and that string
included a three-point victory over the Sun on July 14 in
Minnesota.

"We need to stay hungry and execute," Smith said. "It's tough
in this league. We could easily lose five in a row."

It wasn't likely on this night. The Lynx opened an 18-point lead
in the second half and the Sun never threatened.

The Sun shot a season-low 32 percent, with only Wendy Palmer
reaching double figures with 10 points. The Sun's scoring leader,
Nikes Sales, was held to a season-low four points -- 11 below her
average.

Hold, Minnesota's first-round draft pick out of Kansas State, is
the league's rookie leader in blocks and rebounds. She finished
with seven rebounds and anchored a dominating post for Minnesota.
Tamara William's led the Lynx with 10 rebounds.

"It gives you a good feeling knowing they can handle things on
their own in the middle and you don't have to come down and help
with the double-team," Smith said.

Connecticut could get little done on the inside and was
outrebounded 42-34. The Sun were coming off an 11-day, five-game
road trip, winding it up Wednesday morning with a 10-point victory
over defending champion Detroit.

The Lynx had a four-day layoff, came out firing and never
trailed. Smith hit four 3s in the first half to help Minnesota to a
33-25 point lead at the break.

"By me getting it going, I'm able to set up plays for
someone," Smith said.

The Lynx led by as many as 12 points in the half.

Connecticut used an 8-3 run to cut the margin to six points with
under five minutes to play, but was overmatched inside by
Minnesota's bigger post players and would get no closer in the
half.

With her 27 points, Smith surpassed Andrea Stinson for third
place on the WNBA career scoring list with 3,280.

The Sun have lost four of their last five and continue to
struggle against Western Conference teams. Connecticut is one-half
game out of first in the Eastern Conference with a 10-2 record
against those opponents, but is 2-10 against the Western
Conference.

Smith's six 3-pointers were the most scored by a player against
the Sun this season and Ohlde's five blocks also were a season-high
against Connecticut. The loss was tough to take for Connecticut
coach Mike Thibault.

"I should have stuck with my first instinct," Thibault said.
"Get tossed early so I wouldn't have to watch the rest of this."
